div.div:
Concept & Terminology:
- Building block: Tensor (a multi-dimensional array of numbers)
- Tensor Contiguity: contiguity refers to how tensor elements are stored in memory. Contiguous tensors have their data laid out in a single, uninterrupted block of memory. Non-contiguous tensors, often created through operations like slicing or transposing, might break this sequence.

div.div:
View vs Reshape:
- view(): It’s fast and efficient because it doesn’t copy data but instead reinterprets the existing tensor layout. However, there’s a catch — it only works on contiguous tensors (we’ll get to that shortly).
- reshape(): More flexible, since it handles non-contiguous tensors by creating a new copy if necessary. But this flexibility comes at a potential performance cost.
